This one is for the shotgun collectors out there. I hate to see it one go but need to free up some funds. What I have here is a Savage Fox Model B made in 1942.  It is a hammerless side-by-side 12-gauge double barrel shotgun for sale.  On the barrel it says Proof Tested 12 Gauge, 2 ¾ Inch Chamber.
Fox Savage Arms Corporation, Model B,  Utica, NY Made in U.S.A.  Notice it is not made at Chicopee Falls, Mass or Westfield, Maine. title: For Sale:  Colt 45 1911 01091, 80 Series SS Hand Engraved
location: New York, New York, United States
postcontent: This is the stainless steel 80 Series Government Model of the legendary 1911 pistol, with full coverage (100%) of hand engraving enhancing this weapon. The 1911 issues were used in two World Wars, in the Korean and Vietnam conflict, and became a symbol of the American military might. This handgun is high polished, fully engraved factory new, with only a few modifications: adding a bit larger and more visible front sight and a better pronounced rear sight. The original durable plastic main spring housing is exchanged for a stainless steel housing, which also has the lanyard option. Compared with earlier models, this gun has a more elongated spur on the grip safety, and two half moon shaped grooves on the frame behind the trigger, giving a more convenient index finger position to right and left handed shooters alike. This weapon has two stamped factory original Colt magazines, the factory supplied blue Colt range box, the owners' manual, and the blue safety lock with the Colt logo on it. The gun has the original factory supplied anodized black aluminum trigger. The engraving job on this weapon was performed by Ivan Tibor Mate, an engraver in San Antonio, Texas.

title: For Sale:  FN SPR A1 .308 not Remington 700 or Savage
postcontent:
Unfired FN SPR A1 in factory McMillian stock.  Unfired.  Trigger Job and pillar bedded.  I've had this for at least 4 years, I never got the money together to put the kind of scope on it that it deserves.  For those unfamiliar with the SPR it was basicly a "screw you" from FN to the rest of the precision rifle community.  The story goes that FN was told that they couldn't build a sun-MOA boltgun with a chrome lined barrel.  FN disagreed as, according to them, they had built plenty of sub-MOA M240 barrels.  So they built the SPR with a chrome lined barrel and sub-MOA accuracy.  In most precision rifle the barrel is considered a wear item good got a few hundred to a few thousand rounds, depending on manufacturer and shooter requirements.  The SPR barrel, being chrome lined, should last pretty much forever.  Hence the attraction.

I should keep this, but other projects need funding.  Comes with 4 5rd mags.  Mags are normally $60/each if/when you can find them.  Great rifle, great price 

Call or text

title: For Sale:  WWI WWII Model of 1917 Eddystone Rifle 30.06 M1917 Enfield
location: I-30 and I-430, Little Rock, Arkansas
postcontent:
This is an original issue WWI US Government Model of 1917 Eddystone.  The U.S. Army Ordnance Department accepted the modified Enfield rifle for the use of American troops on May 11, 1917.  .303 Pattern 1914 Mk I rifle production at Eddystone, Pennsylvania effectively ceased in mid-1917, as the plant re-tooled to begin making the U. S. Military Rifles, .30 caliber, Model 1917.

At this time the Remington Arms Company of Delaware employed 10,500 workers at Eddystone, but many were still working on completing the final batches of .303 Pattern 1914 Mk I rifles. Employment decreased to 3,917 on July 15, 1917, but gradually increased to a maximum of 15,409 men and women on September 27, 1918, all working on the U.S. Model 1917 rifles .  Eddystone was awarded a contract for 450,000 rifles; and later another contract for 250,000 for the US Army in WWI.  Production of U.S. Model 1917 rifles at Eddystone began on September 17, 1917, and this facility delivered its first order of 450,000 rifles long before the promised date of June 30, 1918. The second order for 250,000 rifles were also completed by that same date.  The Eddystone Model of 1917 went on to see action through WWII by some troops.

This rifle is one of the rare survivors of the 700,000 Eddystone rifles produced before the US entry into WWI.  The stock is fairly rough and could use some work but this rifle is a great shooter!  The bore is excellent with no rust, strong rifling, and grooves.  It will make a great 30.06 shooting rifle.  Even the barrel is an original WWI barrel.  All WWI inspector marks are still on the receiver and the stock.  The rear hand guard does have a WWI repaired crack that is strong.  Grab this piece of history while you can.

title: For Sale:  Deer Hunting
postcontent:
There is an increasingly alarming trend in sellers noting "Great Deer Rifle" or "Get Ready For Deer Season" for rifles that fire an illegal caliber for hunting deer in Indiana.  I'm not sure if this is a matter of ignorance, and believing that a 30-30 is in fact legal, or if it is just shady business.  In either case, the 30-30 is an excellent deer caliber (along with several others), but it is illegal in Indiana.  Buyers, please know what your state laws are.   

These are the rules that the state of Indiana allows:

*Rifles with cartridges that fire a bullet of .357-inch diameter or larger;

*have a minimum case length of 1.16 inches

*and have a maximum case length of 1.8 inches are legal to use only during the deer firearms and special antler less seasons.

Some cartridges legal for deer hunting include the .357 Magnum, .38-.40 Winchester, .41 Magnum, .41 Special, .44 Magnum, .44 Special, .44-.40 Winchester, .45 Colt, .454 Casull, .458 SOCOM, .475 Linebaugh, .480 Ruger, .50 Action Express, .500 S&W, .460 Smith & Wesson, .450 Bushmaster, and .50 Beowulf.

title: For Sale:  Concealed Carry Permit
postcontent:
A Concealed Carry Permit pertains to carrying a concealed handgun on your person, in your vehicle, or on another person's property.  There are a lot of people demanding proof of Permit or believing they need to provide a Permit in order to buy/sell non-handgun related firearms (even saw a guy selling ammo and requiring a valid permit).  A Concealed Carry Permit is irrelevant on the topic of long guns, i.e. rifles and shotguns, and anything not labeled as a handgun.  Please do not sell and/or purchase firearms until you are aware of your state laws.  This is the kind of ignorance that will come back to bite lawful and well meaning shooters and hunters.  There is no room for ignorance when it comes to firearm safety and knowledge. 

Indiana Concealed Carry Laws
http://www.in.gov/legislative/ic/code/title35/ar47/
